title: Aust bonds up after US Fed comments
text:
Thu, Jul 16, 2015, 9:09 AM AEST - Australia Markets open in 51 mins. Aust bonds up after US Fed comments AAP â€“ 25 minutes ago Print 
The Australian bond market is stronger after a quiet session on global bond markets following unsurprising comments from the US Federal Reserve overnight. 
St George chief economist Hans Kunnen said prices in most major bond markets were little changed after the comments from US Fed chair Janet Yellen "added no fresh insights into monetary policy thinking", and reiterated a US interest rate rise is likely in 2015. 
At 0830 AEST on Thursday, the September 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.005 (implying a yield of 2.995 per cent), up from 96.920 (3.080 per cent) on Wednesday. 
The September 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.000 (2.000 per cent), up from 97.940 (2.060 per cent). 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.993%, from 1.994% Wednesday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 3.115%, unchanged 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* September 2015 bill futures, 97.890, from 97.870 
* December 2015 bill futures, 97.940, from 97.910 
(*Closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
